 have been compromised by the dominant societies by which they have been colonized. Indigenous communities in particular are responding to these opportunities in innovative ways that set them apart from their non-Indigenous predecessors and competitors. Indigenous Tourism Movements explores Indigenous identity using “movement” as a metaphor, drawing on case studies from throughout the world including Botswana, Canada, Chile, Panama, Tanzania, and the United States. Editors Alexis C.Bunten and Nelson Graburn, along with a diverse group of contributors, frame tourism as a critical lens to explore the shifting identity politics of Indigeneity in relation to heritage, global policy, and development. They juxtapose diverse expressions of identity – from the commodification of Indigenous culture to the performance of heritage for tourists – to illuminate the complex local, national, and transnational connections these expressions produce. Indigenous Tourism Movements is a sophisticated, sensitive, and refreshingly frank examination of Indigeneity in the contemporary world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCulture and tourism. 0aHeritage tourismvCase studies. 0aIndigenous peoplesvCase studies. 0aTourismxAnthropological aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh1 aBunn-Marcuse, Kathryn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBunten, Alexis Celeste, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBunten, Alexis Celeste, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDouny, Laurence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiraudo, Rachel F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraburn, Nelson H.H. , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 